lass=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 32<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/25/03 2:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=254.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   How much fallout would a &quot;Conventional&quot; Orion laun</span><hr size=1> How much fallout would an Orion launch actually produce?<br>
<br>
I’ve been thinking about this quite a lot. Though I would prefer to use a pure fusion system I am wondering just how bad a “Conventional” Orion would be. These are some of my thoughts.<br>
<br>
There are important differences between Bombs and Pulse units.<br>
<br>
Bombs are “meant” to be destructive. To that end Fallout is not necessarily a problem and may even be enhanced. Blast effects are maximised and I don’t believe for one minute that bomb designers weren’t cute enough not to deliberately shape the explosion to direct the blast down and outwards.<br>
<br>
Pulse units are “meant” to produce a carefully engineered jet of plasma straight up. Most of the blast is directed upwards in a fairly narrow jet and this would carry most of the fission products (Possibly all with careful attention to pulse unit design) with it, we don’t want “blast” as such and we definitely don’t want fallout. Indeed we don’t really want much fission yield at all. Fission produces the “Wrong kind” of energy. We would in fact want to get as much yield as possible from fusion processes.<br>
<br>
The initial explosion would displace a large amount of air. The jet of plasma, carrying most of the fission fragments, would shoot straight up and as it cools the air would rush in behind it maintaining the upward momentum. With a conventional nuclear explosion this column of plasma would eventually cool to ambient at which point the “head” of the mushroom cloud would normally form. As it cools further the fission fragments that had been supported by the hot plasma would fall to earth.<br>
<br>
But this is not what happens with an Orion! With an Orion Launch, we are getting “Refresher” explosions every second or so. Each new explosion would reheat the plasma from the previous explosions and add its own. It would *never* be allowed to cool. Far beneath the Orion the inrushing air would continue to drive the plasma, with its fission fragment loading, skywards and as the ship accelerates towards space it would carry with it a accelerating plume of fission fragment contaminated plasma. (Much as a sinking ship drags down any survivors that are too close to it). Eventually this plume would leave the atmosphere at a speed, well exceeding the escape velocity, carrying most of the fission fragments with it.<br>
<br>
Is this common knowledge, is it rubbish or is it a new idea that nobody had previously considered??<br>
<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
<br>
