<br>
I have heard the figure of between 10 and 20 (This figure is of course completly meaningless in any significant human terms) What I was curious about was whether this figure was arrived at simply by extrapolating existing *assumptions* on radiation exposure after bomb explosions or whether or not my &quot;Chimney effect&quot; had been taken into consideration.<br>
<br>
If my &quot;Chimney effect&quot; had *not* been taken into consideration then the enviromental effects of a &quot;Conventional&quot; Orion launch could be very much smaller than previously assumed.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
<br>
PS Has the spell checker broken, I can't get it to work anymore?? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 341<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/26/03 4:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=254.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: fission products</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Pulse units are “meant” to produce a carefully engineered jet of plasma straight up. Most of the blast is directed upwards in a fairly narrow jet and this would carry most of the fission products (Possibly all with careful attention to pulse unit design) with it...</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 Not quite. The bomb explosion itself is pretty much omnidirectional, and the bomb itself gets blown every which way.<br>
 For the first few microseconds after critical mass, some of the prompt radiation is reflected inwards by the shell (much like a common 2-stage fission/fusion bomb, somewhat similar to the neutron reflector common in every bomb). At the same time, all the radiation which goes in the direction of the channel filler (leading towards the propellant disc) is facilitated along. Much of the redirected radiation from the reflector shell is also sent this way. While the bomb is heating up and getting ready to fly apart in an omnidirectional radial explosion, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>a proportionally high amount</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of prompt radiation is directed/aided into the channel filler.<br>
 Basically, the channel filler just allows them to get the desired energy into the propellant slab from a proportionally slightly smaller bomb.<br>
 Much of the energy you'd normally expect from a .1kt bomb goes outward as expected (carrying bomb debris with it). A slightly higher than usual amount of energy goes into the propellant, and the vaporised propellant goes towards the ship.<br>
 The fission fragments go their merry own way.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; we don’t want “blast” as such and we definitely don’t want fallout. Indeed we don’t really want much fission yield at all. Fission produces the “Wrong kind” of energy. We would in fact want to get as much yield as possible from fusion processes.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I fail to see why the added difficulty and expense of a 2 stage thermonuclear process is needed for a .1kt up to 20kt bomb.<br>
Fission produces plenty of prompt X rays.<br>
<br>
 I expect the &quot;chimney effect&quot; would be lost in the chaotic flows in the ship's wake.<br>
 In any case, the fission fragments are not favorably sent upwards, propellant plasma is, and it's stopped/slowed considerably in any upwards rush by the ship. If not, then something hasn't been done right, since that's the whole purpose of the exercise.<br>
<br>
 Also add to your fallout calculations the fact that tungsten seems to have been favored as propellant. Add nuclear blast to an already excited plasma of vaporised heavy metal... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/28/03 2:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=254.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re Fission Products</span><hr size=1> What I mean about the “wrong kind” of energy is this;<br>
<br>
It seems to me (and I’m no bomb designer I admit) that a pulse unit is essentially a specialised form of neutron bomb possessing a somewhat directional nature. A sort of neutron cannon as it were. But with the mouth of the barrel plugged with material that would absorb the neutrons and gamma rays.<br>
<br>
It also seems to me that the energy contribution made by nuclear particles other than the neutrons and gammas probably doesn’t help us that much in terms of energising the propellant.<br>
<br>
A single D-T Fusion releases 17.6Mev, of this 14.1Mev (80%) is carried by the neutron (I’m not sure about the gamma contribution). A single U235 fission releases 207MeV, of this only 12Mev comes as Gamma and neutrons. (i.e. around 6%)  I Imagine that This means that (To put it rather crudely) for each Kt of neutron/gamma yield we need 1.25Kt of overall fusion yield but to achieve this with fission yield would take nearly 17Kt of overall fission yield.<br>
<br>
All in all I would prefer my nuclear explosions not to be any bigger than they need to be! Especially if I am only a couple of hundred feet away from them IYSWIM <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
(Of course I may be talking absolute twaddle, if I am, please tell me and tell me why <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
