<br>
I am not sure a fusion bomb would be any cleaner, as you still need the fission trigger, and the amount of Pu in a .1kT trigger or a 1kT trigger is esentialy the same. Critical mass has a lower limit to how much Pu you must assemble. The lower yields are achieved by making the bomb work less efficiently without any reduction in nuclear material. As most pulse units are in the .1-2kT range a pure fission bomb would be the simplest and cheepest.<br>
<br>
Regardless of their direction, most of the fission fragments produced within the atmosphere will likely fall back to Earth, and continue their standard decay orders. The best way to limit fallout effects would be to choose weather conditions which minimize the plumes movement downrange. <p>&quot;If,&quot; he wispered, &quot;if we could only pick that lock....&quot; - , THE WORLD SET FREE</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 40<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/1/03 3:50 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=254.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re Fission fragments</span><hr size=1> Naturally I do not know how a neutron bomb works! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> However I had always thought of a neutron bomb as being a fission-fusion-fission device with the outermost fission bit left out. (IE using a small fission trigger to generate a modest (though not large) fusion detonation) This would produce large amounts of neutrons and gammas but with relatively little fallout. If there are additional processes involved I would love to know what they are! (Yes Really!)<br>
<br>
Similarly I also had the impression that pulse units were intended to use neutron energy as well as gamma energy so a reaction that maximises the amount of neutron/gamma yield whist minimising overall energy would seem to me to be a good idea. (Though I may be wrong)<br>
<br>
The point about small yields is well taken. However I am a fan of large Orion’s, large Orion’s need large pulse units, the environment I am envisaging is one where the total yield is one where a significant fusion yield would not be impractical. Indeed some sort of pure fusion may well not be out of the question. Pure fusion has been elusive for weaponeers but a pulse unit is a different environment with different constraints. What is not possible for a weapon may well work for a pulse unit even if it is expensive, using pure fusion NPU’s to achieve orbit and “conventional” ones afterwards would be good and could give us the unbeatable advantages that ground launched Orion’s could give us.<br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
